ldhood asthma in New Zealand and the Czech Republic, Susanna Trnka traces how ideas about self-management, as well as policies inculcating self-reliance and self-responsibility more broadly, are assumed, reshaped, and ignored altogether by medical professionals, asthma sufferers and parents, environmental activists, and policymakers. By studying nations that share a commitment to the ideals of neoliberalism but approach children's health according to very different cultural, political, and economic priorities, Trnka illuminates how responsibility is reformulated with sometimes surprising results.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAsthma in childrenxGovernment policyxCzech Republic. 0aAsthma in childrenxGovernment policyxNew Zealand. 0aAsthma in childrenxGovernment policyzCzech Republic. 0aAsthma in childrenxGovernment policyzNew Zealand. 0aAsthma in childrenxTreatmentxCzech Republic. 0aAsthma in childrenxTreatmentxNew Zealand. 0aAsthma in childrenxTreatmentzCzech Republic. 0aAsthma in childrenxTreatmentzNew Zealand. 0aMedical policyxCzech Republic. 0aMedical policyxNew Zealand. 0aMedical policyzCzech Republic. 0aMedical policyzNew Zealand. 0aResponsibilityxCzech Republic. 0aResponsibilityxNew Zealand. 0aResponsibilityzCzech Republic. 0aResponsibilityzNew Zealand. 4aCzech Republic. 4aNew Zealand. 4aasthma. 4achildhood. 4aenvironmental health. 4ahealth policy. 4amedicine. 4apatient autonomy. 4aresponsibility. 4aself-management. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360246540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503602465423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503602465.jpg  a978-3-